        What to Expect at a Real Estate Listing Presentation in Brisbane
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A listing presentation is where an agent pitches for the right to sell your property. Here is what a good one looks like, the questions you should ask, and why you should not sign anything at the meeting.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you invite a real estate agent to appraise your property, what follows is typically a listing presentation, also called an appraisal meeting or pitch meeting. It is the agent's opportunity to demonstrate their knowledge of your market, explain how they would approach your campaign, and make a case for why you should choose them to sell your home. Understanding what a good listing presentation involves, and what warning signs to look for in a poor one, will help you make a better decision about who to trust with one of the largest financial transactions of your life.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who attends and what the agent should bring</h2>
      <p>For the seller, every owner of the property should be present if at all possible. Listing decisions made with only one owner in the room create problems later, particularly if co-owners have different views on price, timing, or agent choice. If you co-own the property with a partner or co-investor, arrange for both of you to be there.</p>

      <p>A well-prepared agent will arrive with a comparative market analysis showing recent comparable sales in your suburb and surrounding area, a proposed marketing plan with a recommended VPA (vendor paid advertising) budget and breakdown of where the spend goes, a recommended listing price range supported by the sales evidence rather than by a round number, and a draft Form 6 authority with their proposed commission and terms. Agents who arrive without the comparable sales data or without a concrete marketing recommendation are not prepared for the meeting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to prepare before the agent arrives</h2>
      <p>The listing presentation is not a passive experience. You are interviewing the agent as much as they are presenting to you. Prepare your questions before the meeting rather than trying to think of them on the spot while someone else is running the agenda. Write them down.</p>

      <p>You should also have a clear sense of your own priorities going into the meeting: your preferred timeline for selling, any constraints on access for photography or inspections, and a general sense of what price outcome would satisfy your goals. You do not need to share all of this information upfront, but knowing it yourself means you can evaluate whether the agent's recommendations align with your actual situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to read the price discussion</h2>
      <p>The price discussion is where listing presentations most commonly go wrong. Every vendor wants to hear a high price, and agents who want to win the listing have a financial incentive to tell you what you want to hear. This practice, called overquoting at the listing stage or "buying the listing," is one of the most common problems in residential real estate. An agent quotes an aspirational price to win your business, you list at that price, the market does not respond, and weeks later you are facing price reductions and a stale listing.</p>

      <p>A good agent will show you the comparable sales evidence and explain what it points to, including sales that came in below expectation as well as strong results. They will give you a realistic price range, not a single aspirational figure, and they will be able to explain precisely why their recommended range is supported by the evidence. If an agent's recommended price is significantly higher than two or three others you have spoken to, ask them to walk you through the comparable evidence that supports the difference. If the evidence does not support it, the price is not real.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions every seller should ask at a listing presentation</h2>
      <p>The quality of an agent's answers to specific questions tells you more than the polish of their presentation materials. These are the questions worth asking at every meeting:</p>

      <p><strong>What have you sold in this suburb in the last six months, and how did the results compare to the initial price guidance you gave those vendors?</strong> This question cuts straight to the agent's track record on price accuracy, which is more useful than headline sale prices.</p>

      <p><strong>What is your recommended marketing budget and exactly what does it include?</strong> A vague answer like "it depends" is not sufficient. The agent should be able to give you a specific budget range and explain what portals, photography, and additional marketing it covers.</p>

      <p><strong>How will you communicate with me during the campaign?</strong> Specifically: how often, through what channel, and what information will you provide after each open home? Sellers who feel uninformed during their campaign are consistently less satisfied with the outcome, regardless of the final price.</p>

      <p><strong>What is your plan if we do not receive an acceptable offer in week one?</strong> A good agent will have a clear week-two and week-three strategy, including how they will manage buyer feedback, whether they recommend adjusting the price guidance, and how they approach buyers who have inspected but not made offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Form 6: do not sign at the meeting</h2>
      <p>At some point during the presentation, the agent will likely produce a Form 6 authority, which is the Queensland Property Occupations Act document that authorises an agent to act on your behalf in selling your property. It sets out the commission, the marketing fee, the exclusivity period, and the terms under which the agency relationship operates. It is a legal document, and signing it at the end of a listing presentation is one of the most common mistakes Brisbane sellers make.</p>

      <p>Take the Form 6 away with you. Read it carefully. Pay attention to the commission rate, whether it is percentage-based or fixed, and whether there are any marketing fee clauses that apply regardless of sale outcome. Check the exclusivity period, which is the duration during which you cannot engage another agent. If any terms are unclear, have your solicitor review it before you sign. A good agent will not pressure you to sign on the day, and any agent who does is a warning sign in itself.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Interview at least two or three agents before deciding</h2>
      <p>No matter how impressive any single presentation is, you should speak to at least two or three agents before committing to one. The comparison is valuable not just for evaluating agents but for calibrating your own expectations. If three agents all provide comparable sales evidence pointing to a similar price range, you can have reasonable confidence in that range. If one agent's price is significantly out of step with the others, that is information worth probing.</p>

      <p>Commission rate should be one of several factors in your decision, not the primary one. The cheapest commission is rarely the best value. An agent who achieves a result $50,000 higher than the next-best outcome is worth a higher commission rate. The question to focus on is not what percentage you are paying but what result the agent is likely to produce after their commission is deducted.</p>

